rnwall, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Haskins","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Haskin  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Irish: sometimes adopted for <b>Ó hUiscín</b>; see   Haskin  . More probably, however, it is an altered form of a diminutive of <i>Fuarghus</i>, a personal name meaning ‘cold vigor’."],"variants":[{"name":"Eskins","meanings":["English (Gloucestershire, Worcestershire, and Herefordshire): variant of   Haskins  ."]},{"name":"Haskin","meanings":["English: in northern England, a variant of   Askin   with prosthetic <i>H-</i>.","English: habitational name from Haskayne in Halsall (Lancashire), possibly from Old Welsh <i>hescenn</i> ‘marsh, bog’. There may have been some confusion with   Heskin  ,   Askin  , and   Axon  .","English: in southern England, a post-medieval variant of   Hoskin   with unrounding of the vowel."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":34,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Haskins was born in 1348, in Cornwall, England. She married John Kelly. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1420, in her hometown, at the age of 72."},"et":{"1348–1420":"1348–1420","1346–1410":"1346–1410","1362–1420":"1362–1420","1348":"1348","1346":"1346","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1362":"1362","1382":"1382","England":"England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England"},"fi":{"1348–1420":"1348–1420","1346–1410":"1346–1410","1362–1420":"1362–1420","1348":"1348","1346":"1346","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1362":"1362","1382":"1382","England":"England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England"},"fr":{"1348–1420":"1348–1420","1346–1410":"1346–1410","1362–1420":"1362–1420","1348":"1348","1346":"1346","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1362":"1362","1382":"1382","England":"Angleterre","Cornwall, England":"Cornouailles, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Margaret Haskins est née en 1348, à Cornouailles, Angleterre. Elle a épousé John Kelly. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille. Elle est décédée en 1420, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 72 ans."},"de":{"1348–1420":"1348–1420","1346–1410":"1346–1410","1362–1420":"1362–1420","1348":"1348","1346":"1346","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1362":"1362","1382